<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / Thou shalt not cook the books
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
God, of course, can see through the tricks of creative accountancy. But many
of his servants on earth cannot and have resolved to do something about it.
The effects of woodworm nibbling the pews and the depreciation of collapsing
spires may be shown in the accounts of English cathedrals for the first time
following the creation of a new working party.
The Association of English Cathedrals has set up a group to report next year
on how to present financial information regarding the 42 Anglican cathedrals
in England fairly and consistently.
This follows an analysis of their accounts which showed that there are as
many divergent and incomparable practices as there are cathedrals.
Mr Peter Burnham of accountancy firm Coopers &amp; Lybrand, chairman of the
working party, said the matters to be considered included the valuation and
depreciation of cathedrals and related property, and the treatment of
legacies and donations.
One senior member of the Archbishop's Commission on Cathedrals, which was
set up in 1992 to consider matters including management, said yesterday:
'Cathedral accounting is disgraceful. It's a fascinating aspect of medieval
life. They get up to every trick in the books.'
He said the most scandalous practice was the use of 'off-balance sheet
finance' and 'concealment by canons' to hide in undeclared trusts the true
wealth of cathedrals from the attention of the church hierarchy.
The Cathedrals Measure of 1963 required accounts to be audited and
published. But it provided no guide-lines, and the Church commissioners do
not examine the accounts in any detail.
Equally important, medieval law dictates that the dean and canons of a
cathedral, once appointed, form a 'corporation spiritual' immune even from
the power of visiting bishops. Mr Burnham said: 'They are accountable only
to God.'
Mr Malcolm Hoskins of Touche Ross, a member of the working party who has
audited a cathedral in the past, said, perhaps rather inappropriately:
'Cathedrals are ancient buildings that need a hell of a lot of work (for
their upkeep). 'Like any other charity, if anything the incentive is not to
appear too financially healthy.'
</TEXT>
