<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / Names 'may sue compiler of league tables'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sturge Holdings, the Lloyd's agency, yesterday issued an injunction against
Mr John Rew, the co-editor of Chatset league tables of performance on the
insurance market. The action concerns alleged breaches of confidentiality in
publication of sensitive information.
Sturge warned that the action may lead to Names - individuals whose assets
have traditionally supported the market - on its syndicates suing Mr Rew,
who is chairman of their own action group.
The writ alleges that Mr Rew published information relating to Sturge
syndicates provided to him as chairman of the Sturge Names Action Group. It
seeks damages and interest for breach of contract and breach of confidence
for disclosing information provided in connection with the evaluation of the
legal disputes initiative launched by Lloyd's.
Sturge claims this information was circulated by Mr Rew in the Chatset
league tables last week, and also in a newsletter.
Sturge's concerns focus on 210, a non-marine syndicate. The Chatset guide
provides details including a memo to the board suggesting run-off figures of
up to Dollars 800m.
Mr James Macdonald, group finance director, said the information was highly
sensitive and its distribution to potential claimants, reinsurers and others
on the market could be extremely prejudicial.
'We are not trying to say the figures are wrong,' he said. 'This raises
questions about the whole way in which Chatset gets its information and then
purports to be an authority on Lloyd's'
Mr Rew yesterday called the writ 'codswallop' and said it would be
contested. 'The information belongs to Lloyd's Names. Any Name is entitled
to get it,' he said. 'Most are just not in a position to broadcast it.'
Chatset, which has proved a long-standing irritant to Lloyd's, last week
predicted that Names would face demands of up to Pounds 8.65bn from the
insurance market during the next 20 years.
The league tables have been published since the late 1970s and have long
been criticised by Lloyd's, but they have often proved accurate.
'The origin of Chatset was getting syndicate accounts which we were told
were secret,' said Mr Rew. 'The point has always been to make Lloyd's more
transparent but it's so hopelessly opaque.'
The High Court yesterday upheld the right of Lloyd's to pay out losses from
its central fund and recover these sums from Names to discharge their
underwriting obligations. Mr Justice Saville ruled that defences and
counter-claims put forward by Names as preliminary issues before legal
action were unfounded.
</TEXT>
