<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / Argentine city hit by job protests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BARHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUENOS AIRES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Argentine government last night flew riot police from Buenos Aires to
retake the north-western city of Santiago del Estero from rioters.
Local police withdrew from the city's streets after rioters stormed the
governor's palace and pillaged the building. They then rampaged through the
courthouse and legislature, which they tried to burn down.
The rioting broke out after the provincial government announced plans to cut
jobs as part of an economic reform programme. Santiago del Estero is one of
Argentina's poorest provinces. One rioter said: 'We are all (dying) of
hunger. We are in the office of some thief and we are breaking everything.'
The uprising forced President Carlos Menem to cut short a visit to the
Vatican.
Earlier in the day, rioters and police traded gunfire, molotov cocktails,
stones and tear gas. Two were reported dead and dozens injured. Crowds later
fanned out through the city, ransacking the homes of prominent local
politicians, including that of Mr Fernando Lobo, the recently appointed
provincial governor.
This is the second, and most serious, recent outbreak of violence in
Argentina's provinces.
The deteriorating economies of many provinces is emerging as one of Mr
Menem's most pressing political and economic challenges. The federal
government is demanding that Argentina's 23 provinces reform their chaotic
finances by cutting public jobs, reducing spending and reforming their tax
systems. They rely on tax transfers from Buenos Aires to cover two-thirds of
their annual spending of Dollars 20bn.
</TEXT>
