<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / China and Japan skew US deficit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US trade deficit is becoming increasingly unbalanced regionally, with
most of the shortfall accounted for by Japan and China, official figures
indicated yesterday, writes Michael Prowse in Washington.
The overall merchandise trade deficit declined slightly in October, to
Dollars 10.46bn (Pounds 7bn), against Dollars 10.62bn in September, roughly
in line with analysts' projections.
But the deficit with Japan rose 14 per cent to Dollars 6.1bn, the highest
since November 1986. That with China rose 8 per cent to Dollars 2.7bn. For
the year to date the combined deficit with Japan and China was Dollars
67.6bn, more than two thirds of the overall deficit.
By contrast, trade with the European Union is virtually in balance, with a
negligible US deficit of Dollars 11m so far this year.
