<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / Germans defend recycling scheme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARIANE GENILLARD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Klaus Topfer, the German environment minister, yesterday defended his
country's recycling scheme following a decision by European environment
ministers to introduce lower European recycling quotas than those in
Germany, writes Ariane Genillard in Bonn.
In a statement, Mr Topfer, the architect of Germany's ambitious
environmental legislation, said the agreement would set back recycling
programmes in Europe and force Germany to produce more waste.
'It is not supposed to be the EU's job to standardise the environmental
tempo in all member states at any price or even to reverse it,' Mr Topfer
said.
