<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 93 / Markets Report: Dollar firms against yen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CONNER MIDDELMANN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The US dollar rose to a five-month high against the Japanese yen and is
expected to test Y110 today, writes Conner Middelmann.
The dollar strengthened to Y109.86 before closing at Y109.65, up from
Y109.35 on Tuesday. It finished New York trading at Y109.76. It received a
lift from Tuesday's November trade figures, showing Japan's trade surplus
against the US narrowing for the first time in nearly three years, and a
stream of strong US economic data at a time when the Japanese economy
remains troubled.
Moreover, expectations of a reduction soon in Japan's 1.75 per cent official
discount rate to stimulate the economy are keeping the yen under pressure.
'With the fiscal package delayed, the onus is once again on monetary policy
to help the economy, and the Bank of Japan is coming under increased
pressure to ease,' said Mr Stephen King, deputy chief economist at James
Capel. He expects the dollar to trade around Y121 by the end of 1994 and
predicts Y130 for the second half of 1995. 'Interest rates will stay low,
and when the recovery does come, it will be weak by historical standards,'
he added.
The US currency also gained more ground against the D-Mark on residual hopes
that the Bundesbank's central bank council would cut official interest rates
at its meeting today. It ended at DM1.7160, up from DM1.7135 but off the
day's high of DM1.7205. It closed in New York at DM1.7172.
The resolution of the Gatt world trade talks had next to no impact on the
currency market, with an agreement already heavily discounted for days. 'The
market is relieved all the brinkmanship of the last weeks is over and it can
settle down to business as usual,' said Mr King.
In the UK money market, the short-term sterling interest rate contract slid
sharply on disappointment that the Bank of England did not lower interest
rates following the better than expected inflation numbers. This offered an
opportunity for many traders holding long positions in the contract to take
profits after its recent strong run.
The November retail prices index excluding mortgage interest payments rose
by 2.5 per cent year-on-year, after a 2.8 per cent increase in October. The
headline inflation rate came in at 1.4 per cent last month, the same as in
October.
Immediately after the RPI release, the March short sterling contract jumped
to 95.00, but when the Bank of England's operations made it clear that there
would be no immediate rate cut, the contract quickly sold off to a low of
94.81. It ended at 94.85, down 0.09 point from Tuesday.
A senior money dealer commented: 'It was an overbought market, and too many
people were long of it.'
There are still lingering hopes that the UK central bank could announce a
rate reduction later this week, although the shake-out in the futures pit
indicated that those have waned significantly.
Market conditions remained tight, causing money rates at the short end to
firm again. The Bank of England announced a shortage of Pounds 2.65bn, which
was later revised down to Pounds 2.5bn. In early operations it purchased
bills totalling Pounds 1.65bn for resale to the market on January 5 and 6 at
5 13/32 per cent. In further operations, the Bank bought bills amounting to
Pounds 37m, followed by another Pounds 190m in the afternoon and late
assistance of around Pounds 645m.
As long as residual hopes for a near-term rate cut persist, the Bank will
keep a tight grip on market liquidity, said a trader. But if the Bundesbank
leaves rates unchanged today and hopes for a base rate cut wane further,
'the Bank will probably ease off and money market conditions could relax',
he predicted.
'I do not see another base rate cut this year - the signals the authorities
have given are very, very clear,' said Mr Philip Shaw, group economist at
Union Discount, one of the eight London discount houses.
Sterling eased to DM2.450 against the D-Mark from DM2.550 in thin turnover.
The French franc advanced further against the D-Mark, boosted by the Gatt
world trade agreement and hopes of more French easing. Contrary to perceived
economic wisdom, rate cuts tend to bolster the French currency on hopes that
they will stimulate the sluggish economy.
The franc finished at FFr3.418 per D-Mark, up from the previous day's
FFr3.422 close. It hit a high of FFr3.4128 during the day, boosted by a call
for lower interest rates by Prime Minister Edouard Balladur. He told
parliament in a speech that lower rates were a necessary condition for
economic recovery in France.
The French currency's continued strength indicates that even if the
Bundesbank leaves rates unchanged today, there is a reasonable chance of
French easing before Christmas, said Capel's Mr King. 'With the franc at
this level, they must be rebuilding reserves very quickly and must be
seriously thinking about lowering rates,' he added.
The remaining currencies in Europe's exchange rate mechanism were little
altered against the D-Mark.
The Belgian franc was unchanged at BFr20.86 to the D-Mark. The Danish krone
ended at DKr3.923, down from DKr3.916 on Tuesday. The Italian lira finished
at L987.0 against the D-Mark, barely changed from L987.1 the previous day.
