<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 93 / Stock exchange debates successor to USM
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The London Stock Exchange board will today consider a proposal to create a
separately managed exchange with its own chief executive to handle trading
in the shares of smaller companies.
This 'Enterprise Market' would operate under the aegis of the main stock
exchange, which would retain control over certain of its activities.
The proposal, contained in a report from the stock exchange's smaller
companies working party, says that separate management is needed to
distinguish the companies with shares trading on the new exchange. The only
alternative would be to give the new exchange lower regulatory requirements.
The report will say that unless the new market has either separate
management or lighter regulation it will never be able to distinguish itself
from the main exchange and thus will have little reason for its creation.
The board could either approve the report in its entirety or reject some of
the recommendations. It will be released as a consultation document.
The question of governance is believed to be the most controversial aspect
of the proposed new market, intended as a successor to the Unlisted
Securities Market, which closed earlier this year.
Venture capitalists and others involved in the promotion of small companies
believe a less regulated market would never gain public confidence. Indeed,
they have proposed that the new market require more frequent trading
statements than the main exchange.
However, the stock exchange is said to be uneasy about ceding too much
authority to a separate body. Also, in the light of recent amendments to
stock exchange rules, making it easier for small or new companies to have
their shares traded on the Official List, the exchange is said to have been
sceptical about whether there was sufficient justification for the new
market.
The report was delayed by the illness of the committee's former chairman, Mr
Ian MacPherson, chairman of Low and Bonar. There were also internal
divisions, particularly between industry members and stock exchange
representatives. The report urges the creation of the Enterprise Market as a
distinct market under the aegis of the stock exchange. It is understood
requirements would differ little from those of the USM. The new entity would
embark on a marketing campaign to attract high growth companies.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
