<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 93 / Upturn can withstand tax rises, Clarke says: Underlying
inflation rate at 26-year low of 2.5%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER and PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK economy is recovering strongly enough to withstand tax increases
planned over the next two years, Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, said
yesterday.
He told the House of Commons Treasury and Civil Service Committee that
recovery, helped by low interest rates and a 'spectacularly good' outlook
for inflation, was 'established and strong enough' to survive the planned
fiscal tightening.
His comments came as official figures showed the Treasury's preferred
measure of underlying inflation - the year-on-year rise in the retail prices
index excluding mortgage interest payments - falling to its lowest level for
26 years at 2.5 per cent last month, compared with 2.8 per cent in October.
The headline rate was unchanged at 1.4 per cent.
Although price pressures in the economy seemed 'pretty well under control',
he said the government would take no risks with inflation and would not
hesitate to raise interest rates should pressures start to pick up.
However, Mr Clarke said he was 'pretty confident that we will not get into
trouble' with the government's 1 per cent-4 per cent target for underlying
inflation 'in the near future'.
He said the real test of the government's policy would be keeping inflation
down and maintaining competitiveness once people believed economic recovery
was established.
Mr Clarke acknowledged that the cumulative taxation effect of the two
Budgets this year would amount to between Pounds 15bn and Pounds 17bn in
three years' time, or the equivalent of 7p on the basic rate of income tax.
He described the tax rises as necessary to bring public finances back in
order, adding that the way in which the revenue would be raised was
politically acceptable.
'The first thing I had to do was to make sure that we had taken the
necessary decisions to deal with the level of borrowing and the public
finances,' he said.
'I looked for increases in taxation which were best judged to be supported
by the general public and best judged to have minimum adverse impact on the
economy.'
Mr Clarke said he had no target level for sterling in mind as the government
set policy based on a range of monetary and asset value factors.
Food price falls help inflation figure, Page 9
Bonds, Page 27
Currencies, Page 29
London stocks, Page 38
