<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 93 / Aspin quits as US defence secretary
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Les Aspin last night abruptly ended an often controversial tenure as US
defence secretary by submitting his resignation to President Bill Clinton.
Appearing with the president at the White House, Mr Aspin, citing 'personal
reasons', said it was 'time to take a break and undertake a new line of
work'.
Mr Clinton, who apparently did not seek the resignation, was lavish in his
praises of the 55-year-old Mr Aspin, the first member of his cabinet to
depart. His resignation takes effect on January 20, by when a replacement,
who is subject to Senate confirmation, is expected to be named.
Names which may be considered include Mr James Woolsey, head of the CIA,
Senator Sam Nunn of Georgia, Congressman Dave McCurdy of Oklahoma and
Admiral William Crowe, a close Clinton adviser and due to be the next US
ambassador to London.
The president commended the 'comprehensive review' of US military structure
Mr Aspin completed in September and which is designed to meet the needs of
the post-Cold War era.
Mr Aspin's health has been a source of concern all year. He underwent heart
bypass surgery this year and although he has claimed to have made a full
recovery his very heavy workload may have exacted a further toll. He has
also come under fire, along with Mr Warren Christopher, the secretary of
state, and Mr Anthony Lake, the national security adviser, for failing
effectively to articulate US foreign policy.
More specific criticism has been directed at his refusal to approve a
request for more heavily armed equipment for US troops in Somalia, prior to
the disastrous Mogadishu firefight in early October which cost the lives of
18 US servicemen.
Mr Aspin also bore the brunt of implementing Mr Clinton's controversial
policy of ending the military's ban on homosexuals. This rendered him
unpopular with many senior serving officers, as did his restructuring of the
military's overall mission, which entails a substantial reduction in real
terms in defence spending over the next five years.
Two weeks ago Mr Aspin implied that defence cuts might have been too deep,
prompting budget director Mr Leon Panetta to doubt that additional funding
could be made available. There is, however, no hard evidence that this
intra-administration fight was a factor in his decision to leave.
</TEXT>
