<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 93 / The Thorp Go-ahead: Greenpeace set for court fight
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Greenpeace, the environmental pressure group which has most vigorously
opposed the licensing of the Thorp plant in Cumbria, was last night
preparing a final challenge by asking the courts for judicial review of the
decision to allow it to operate.
But Greenpeace's supporters are concerned that the move could jeopardise its
finances. British Nuclear Fuels, the plant's owner, has made no secret of
the fact that it hopes costs will curb Greenpeace's ability to campaign.
Yesterday's announcement allows BNF to start full operation of the plant in
28 days, which allows time for legal action before the first load of fuel
makes the plant radioactive.
Greenpeace, whose headquarters in Islington, north London, has been
dominated by the Thorp campaign for more than a year, believes judicial
review will be granted within days. If granted a review, the pressure group
will argue that the government has acted illegally in not holding a public
inquiry, and in particular, that it has not taken enough account of health
risks.
The High Court judge's decision is likely to be final.
The risk Greenpeace is running in tackling Thorp through the courts is that
if it loses, it will face huge legal bills. In September Greenpeace lost a
court battle to prevent BNF testing the plant with uranium and was told to
pay all of the government's costs and two-thirds of BNF's costs.
Greenpeace says it has not yet received the bill from Freshfields, BNF's
solicitors. But it warned its supporters several weeks ago that the bill for
that round could be Pounds 250,000.
So far, Greenpeace has met its costs from its UK finances. Although
fundraising from its 400,000 UK supporters - 2,500 in Cumbria - has suffered
during the recession, Greenpeace UK's income last year was Pounds 4.1m net
of fundraising expenses, compared with Pounds 3.8m in 1991.
If it lost a further court action its campaigning might be seriously dented.
Lord Peter Melchett, executive director of Greenpeace UK, said he expected
to be able to meet the costs if Greenpeace lost, but that if necessary they
could be paid from international funds. Greenpeace's annual worldwide income
has hovered around Dollars 150m since 1990.
</TEXT>
<XX>
