<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 93 / The Joint Statement on Ulster: Suspicion remains rooted in
opposing communities - The reactions of Protestants and Catholics in Belfast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In the Berlin Arms on the Shankill Road in loyalist west Belfast yesterday,
John, a 68-year-old retired postman and one-time Irish fusilier, turned his
back on the television image of a British and Irish prime minister and gazed
into his pint of stout with an air of disgust.
'This is a lot of eye wash. They're not being straight with us. We are ready
to fight here. And they had better bloody believe it.'
A sense of suspicion if not betrayal about what lies behind the declaration
appears to run deep through the unionist grassroots.
The Berlin Arms is just a block away from the scene of a recent IRA bomb
attack. The pub, protected by a security door, is a place of assembly for
Protestants who feel threatened not just by the IRA but by the concept of
Irish unity they suspect is the real purpose behind the complex wording of
the declaration.
Mr Major may seek to reassure this community with his constitutional
guarantees, but the Shankill's history has bred gut reactions rather than
political analysis.
John, who would not give his full name for fear of IRA reprisal, showed me
his Orange Cross - a loyalist identity card with the following statement: 'I
am a loyal British subject pledged to uphold the constitution of our country
against republicanism and subversion.'
Next to him, 30-year-old Mr Brian Warnock, a motor mechanic, admitted to
having 'some Catholic friends' and not being opposed to Sinn Fein being
brought into talks if the IRA renounced violence 'for ever'. But he echoed
the older man's deeper sentiment.
'I am suspicious because Dublin is involved. I think that means we could get
sold down the river.'
Elsewhere in Ulster, some Catholics were disappointed with the agreement,
and thought it might not persuade the IRA to stop.
One man admitted: 'When you see the unionists on television smirking and
telling us they're happy enough, you begin to think: 'Right, they are going
to screw us, aren't they?'
'I want the peace. I could take you to 10 houses right now, and nine of them
agree with me. They've had enough. It's the guy in the tenth house I worry
about. He may not be ready to pack in.'
Mrs Joyce McCartan, a 65-year-old Catholic who has lost 12 family members in
the violence, was more optimistic: 'We have a real chance here, and if
people like Paisley and Robinson keep their mouths shut, then we can get the
peace we all desire.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
