<DATE>931216
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 93 / The Joint Statement: Dublin invites debate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Irish government says it will not spell out in advance which issues it
considers might represent a threat to the unionist community's ethos and way
of life, or which 'can be represented as not being fully consistent with a
modern democratic and pluralistic society', as noted in paragraph six of the
joint declaration.
Dublin says it is prepared to discuss and consider 'ways of removing such
obstacles' but that it is for the unionists to present a list of concerns.
Apart from the clauses in Ireland's constitution that lay claim to the
province, the clause means that issues in areas such as divorce and abortion
are likely to be raised. Legalisation of the former and easing of
restrictions on the latter are due to go through the Dail next year.
The continuing strong influence of the Catholic church over school
curriculums in the Irish republic is also likely to prove a highly
contentious issue with Ulster's Protestants. Education reforms are under way
in the south, but the Catholic church hierarchy is fiercely challenging any
erosion of its power.
Unionist parties are also to be invited to join the proposed Forum for Peace
and Reconciliation, together with other parties in both parts of the island.
This is designed 'to be a consultative body but without any legislative
powers', according to a government spokesman.
However Mr Reynolds indicated yesterday that the real objective of such a
forum was to provide a further incentive for Sinn Fein to renounce violence
by offering it an early role in the negotiating process.
He said in his address to the Irish parliament yesterday that the forum
would be established 'after a real cessation of violence'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>IEZ  Ireland, EC.
</CN>
