<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 93 / No sign of upturn in pay settlements
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There is still no sign of an upturn in pay settlements, with the median
settlement at 2 per cent in the three months to the end of October, the
latest pay bulletin from Industrial Relations Services shows, David Goodhart
writes.
The independent research organisation says that the 2 per cent figure is 0.2
points down from the median figure for the three months to the end of
September.
One sector where pay appears to be rising slightly faster is building
societies.
Recent rises have been significantly above inflation with a minimum pay-bill
cost of 2.5 per cent. The Yorkshire Building Society was the most generous
with an annualised increase of 4.6 per cent.
IRS says the average pay rise for the hotel and catering industry as a whole
this year was 1.6 per cent. Nearly one in three of the sample of 32
employers implemented a pay freeze this year.
Industrial Relations Services, Report 341. IRS, 18-20 Highbury Place, London
N5 1QP.
