<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 93 / Food price falls help inflation to 26-year low: Steady
increase in volume of retail sales shows consumers pushing economy towards
recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Treasury's preferred measure of underlying inflation fell in November to
its lowest level for 26 years, led by lower prices of food, second-hand cars
and alcoholic drinks.
At the same time the volume of retail sales continued its steady rise,
confirming the view that consumers are slowly helping the economy to
recover.
The retail prices index, excluding mortgage interest payments, rose in the
year to November by 2.5 per cent, after 2.8 per cent in the year to October.
The headline inflation rate - the year-on-year rise in the RPI - was 1.4 per
cent last month, the same as in October.
The figures from the Central Statistical Office underline the weakness of
retail price pressures. This is caused by shops cutting prices in a bid to
build volumes and also by only muted rises in retailers' wage costs and the
prices of products bought from wholesalers.
Between October and November the RPI - which reflects the prices of a basket
of 600 goods and services bought by households - fell 0.1 per cent from
141.8 to 141.6. In the six months to November the index rose by just 0.3 per
cent.
A big factor behind last month's weak inflation was a 0.7 per cent fall
between October and November in prices of non-seasonal foods, the biggest in
any month since June 1963.
This was due largely to widespread price-cutting in supermarkets,
particularly on soft drinks, bread, milk, tinned fish and a range of
processed foods.
In the year to November non-seasonal foods rose in price by a weak 1.9 per
cent. In the same period all foods, including fruit and vegetables, affected
by seasonal changes rose 1.4 per cent in price.
Foods which have seen big reductions on the year include fresh fish, down 10
per cent, and pork, down 4 per cent.
The average used car cost 2.9 per cent less last month than in October,
which helped to push motoring costs including petrol down 1.4 per cent on
the month, the biggest one-month fall for three years. In the year to last
month motoring costs rose 3.5 per cent.
Alcoholic drinks fell 0.5 per cent in price on the month, partly because
many off-licences have cut prices in the hope of boosting pre-Christmas
sales. In the year to November prices of these items increased 3.6 per cent,
the lowest figure since 1988.
Household goods including furniture, carpets and electrical equipment rose
0.5 per cent in price on the month, for a weak 0.9 per cent increase in the
year to November. This was the smallest year-on-year rise since the CSO
started records in 1974 and illustrates how the lacklustre housing market
and pressure on disposable incomes is holding back demand.
Other figures from the CSO showed that last month retail sales climbed a
seasonally adjusted 0.4 per cent from October, after a revised 0.3 per cent
increase the previous month.
Between September and November retail volumes rose 0.9 per cent compared
with the June to August period, after a 1.2 per cent increase in the
previous three months. In the year to the last three-month period volumes
were up a healthy 3.6 per cent.
The British Retail Consortium, a trade body, provided an element of festive
cheer by saying sales of Christmas decorations and crackers in recent weeks
had been 'well above' last year's levels.
It said shops selling footwear, medicines and do-it-yourself goods had
performed particularly strongly last month, while sales of electrical goods
and carpets had been disappointing.
Yesterday's inflation-adjusted figures underline how shop sales - which
account for about a quarter of gross domestic product - form one of the
strongest elements behind the UK's recent economic growth.
According to the CSO, mixed retail businesses selling food and non-edible
items had a fairly strong autumn, with sales volumes up 1.4 per cent on a
three-month basis. In the year to the last three-month period these stores
pushed up sales by 5 per cent.
Food retailers saw sales rise 0.7 per cent between September and November
compared with the previous three months. Over the year sales increased by
2.6 per cent.
Retailers specialising in household goods increased sales by 2.4 per cent on
a three-month basis and 9.5 per cent compared with a year ago. Clothing and
shoe shops did less well, with sales rising a muted 2.1 per cent on a yearly
basis and showing a 0.1 per cent decline over the past three months compared
with the June to August period.
The CSO said that, based on non-seasonally adjusted data, the average weekly
value of retail sales last month was Pounds 3.11bn, up 6 per cent on
November last year.
