<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 93 / Sea power generator will be installed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON, Science Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A Pounds 3m wave energy machine is to be installed off the Caithness coast
next year. The Osprey, a full-scale 2MW prototype, is designed to generate
'clean, safe power' in a wide variety of off-shore sites.
'This is the first wave power device that can be mass-manufactured,' said Mr
Allan Thomson, managing director of Applied Research and Technology, the
Inverness-based engineering company developing Osprey.
Osprey will be installed close to AEA Technology's Dounreay nuclear plant
and be linked to the electrical grid by power lines installed for the
Dounreay Fast Reactor which is due to close next year.
It is a partially submerged bell-shaped device containing a column of water.
As the water rises and falls, it pushes air through a turbine. The project
is backed by the European Union, Scottish Enterprise, Highlands and Islands
Enterprise, British Steel, GEC Alsthom, Scottish Hydro-Electric and AEA
Technology.
</TEXT>
