<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 93 / Electricity regulator to force reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Professor Stephen Littlechild, the electricity industry regulator, said
yesterday that he would not need to refer the UK's two main generators to
the Monopolies and Mergers Commission providing he could reach agreement
with them on plant disposals and prices.
He said he had decided to take some action after his inquiry into the
generators' margins and costs. He expected to be able to decide by
mid-January whether a reference to the commission would be necessary.
Prof Littlechild said he had written to the electricity pool, the wholesale
market through which power is traded in England and Wales, to urge early
examination of several reforms including changes to the pricing mechanisms.
Some analysts interpreted his statement as welcome news for National Power
and PowerGen, arguing that his choice of words implied that his preference
was for avoiding a referral. Others said the regulator and the companies had
to overcome considerable obstacles to reach an accommodation. The generators
are extremely reluctant to accept either price controls or plant disposals.
Yesterday, the regulator said steps needed to be taken to 'ensure that
customers are adequately protected in future'. He wanted to open the way for
voluntary sale by the generators of some plant, and said he wanted
'assurances on prices for a reasonable period until a more competitive
market is achieved'.
National Power said it hoped to find a mutually satisfactory way forward
with the regulator. PowerGen said it believed a reference to the commission
was unnecessary but would face it with confidence.
Prof Littlechild's suggested examination of pool price reforms included the
possibility of allowing electricity to be traded outside the pool. He also
urged consideration of a change in pricing mechanisms so that generators
would be paid the price they ask for. At present the pool price is
determined by the price of the most expensive plant.
He also proposed measures aimed at reducing the cost of administration in
the pool price. He wants National Grid to assume responsibility for these
services from April.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
