<DOCNO>FT934-2025</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DLPC5AA9FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931216
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 93 / The GATT Deal: Slender success in attacking barriers -
Services
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL, World Trade Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
One of the great breakthroughs of the Uruguay Round was intended to be its
assault on barriers to trade in services. In the end, achievements have been
modest.
Unbreachable disagreements between the US and the European Union over
financial services, audiovisual services and shipping have left the lion's
share of the agreement unresolved. Along with telecommunications, the
promise is to negotiate deals on these sectors over the coming two years.
Air transport was excluded from the outset.
The residual activity is far from insignificant, covering tourism,
construction, professional services, consultancies, and a limited easing on
movement of workers - but this is small by comparison with the sectors
blighted by dispute.
Only in recent years have governments come to appreciate the importance of
services in international trade. Last year, cross-border services business
was valued at Dollars 900bn, with the foreign operations of services
companies amounting to more than Dollars 3 trillion.
This knowledge led powerful business lobbies, in the US in particular, to
campaign hard in the early days of the Round for ambitious market-opening in
banking, securities, and insurance. But later, it became clear that
countries targeted for liberalisation - like Japan, Korea, the six Asean
states of Singapore, Thailand, the Philippines, Indonesia, Malaysia and
Brunei, and a number of Latin American countries - were not willing or able
to open their markets as wide as American companies hoped, US negotiators
slammed the brakes on their own market-opening commitments.
Haggling over Europe's efforts to protect its film and television sectors on
the grounds of protecting local culture erupted over a year ago. US
audiovisual exports to Europe earned over Dollars 3.5bn last year, and the
US industry did not take kindly to EU plans to cap their access to the
market.
More recently, in financial services, the US decision to offer full
most-favoured-nation rights to just 20-odd industrial economies, following
disappointment over the offers coming from target countries, triggered
uproar among Gatt negotiators. The US has finally backed away from its
threat, but only to allow a further two years of negotiation aimed at
improving access.
Mr Larry Summers, US assistant treasury secretary, reflected the
frustrations of US services industries when he said this week: 'We have not
achieved what the US financial services industry was hoping to achieve in
1986.'
But other negotiators bring a different perspective. 'At Punta del Este
(where the Round was launched), we were talking only of a framework of rules
for services,' one said. 'It was only in 1990 that countries raised their
sights to the idea of getting commitments to liberalise. it is true that
most offers today give no more than standstills, but at least that is a
start. They provide a foundation for us to work from in future rounds.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>CHZ  Switzerland, West Europe.
    QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
    P60   Depository Institutions.
    P61   Nondepository Institutions.
    P62   Security and Commodity Brokers.
    P63   Insurance Carriers.
    P44   Water Transportation.
    P48   Communications.
    P78   Motion Pictures.
</IN>
<XX>
