<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 93 / Greenspan angry at banking plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the US Federal Reserve, has launched a
scathing attack on administration proposals for overhauling US bank
regulation.
He says the plan to transfer regulatory powers from the Fed to a single new
banking commission would seriously undermine the Fed's ability to respond to
potential financial crises and reduce the quality of bank supervision by
removing important 'checks and balances' in the current system of multiple
regulators.
It would also make the Fed less sensitive to monetary conditions and thus
threaten the efficiency of monetary policy.
Mr Greenspan's criticisms are contained in a rare signed article in today's
Wall Street Journal.
The Clinton administration has proposed that a new Federal Banking
Commission should assume regulatory powers now divided among the Fed, the
Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation, the Comptroller of the Currency and
the Office of Thrift Supervision. Under the plan the Fed would lose its
regulatory authority over about 1,000 banks and 6,300 bank holding
companies.
Officials say consolidation of regulatory powers in one agency would
eliminate duplication and create a simpler, more consistent regulatory
system. The Fed would have access to all information collated by the new
commission.
Mr Greenspan says it 'is unrealistic and unduly hopeful to believe that the
knowledge and expertise the Federal Reserve needs to do its job properly can
be gained from studying the exam reports of another agency, having narrow
authority to examine the payments system, or having representation on the
board of a monolithic regulatory institution.'
He concedes the present regulatory system 'has not been functioning
efficiently in recent years' but says there are many alternative solutions.
</TEXT>
