<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / UK Company News: A North Sea hot potato
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Emerald Producer, the floating oil production platform written down by
more than Pounds 42m by Trafalgar House yesterday, has consistently proved a
problem child for its owners.
Most spectacularly it was behind the effective demise of Davy Corporation,
founded in 1830, as the UK's largest independent engineering contractor.
It was originally a drilling rig, owned by Midland &amp; Scottish Resources,
operator of the Emerald oilfield east of Shetland. Midland sold it to Davy
in 1989, at the same time awarding Davy a contract to convert it into a
production platform.
Davy was then to sell the platform back to Midland for a fixed price of
Pounds 118.8m in August 1990. But Davy had difficulties managing the
conversion. Losses on the contract eventually ran almost as high as the
contract price at Pounds 114m.
Trafalgar then took Davy over and agreed in May last year to lease the
platform to Midland for Dollars 65,000 a day. Midland, which is still
operating the platform in the Emerald field, found that production failed to
live up to expectations.
Initial estimates suggested that the field would produce 30,000 barrels a
day for the first two years of its life. It kicked in with a peak of 25,000
b/d in August last year, but this has dwindled to 16,000 b/d.
As a result Midland in August wrote off the entire value of the Emerald
Field development. The provision of Pounds 97m put the company Pounds 113.6m
in the red for 1992 on turnover of Pounds 28.1m.
In September the company defaulted on its charter payments to Trafalgar. Mr
John Hawksley, managing director, said yesterday that the company was in
discussions with Trafalgar to rearrange the charter to fit in better with
the likely production and economic life of the field.
Trafalgar said the Emerald Producer had been carried in the balance sheet at
September 30 at Pounds 66m, a figure supported by independent valuers.
Following the default and reduced life expectation of the field, it is
writing the value down by Pounds 42.1m and making a Pounds 9.5m provision
for costs pending its redeployment or sale.
The results show that turnover from the platform fell from Pounds 16.9m to
Pounds 15.8m for the year to September.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Trafalgar House.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P1389 Oil and Gas Field Services, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 20
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT934-2156</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DLOCPAETFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931215
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / UK Company News: Vaux up to Pounds 27m but no full recovery
yet
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Difficult trading conditions in the hotel and brewing industry held pre-tax
profits at Vaux Group to Pounds 26.6m, compared with Pounds 20.4m, in the
year to September 30.
Although the switch to FRS 3 suggested profits had increased by 31 per cent,
the regional brewer, hotels and nursing homes operator said that, excluding
income from property disposals and the sale of its Blayney's off-licence
chain in 1992, profits increased by a more sluggish 7.1 per cent from Pounds
24.8m.
Sir Paul Nicholson, chairman of the Sunderland-based company, said operating
profits had improved in all divisions despite the lingering impact of the
recession.
Trading profits rose 8.6 per cent to Pounds 42.9m (Pounds 39.5m) on turnover
5 per cent lower at Pounds 234.9m (Pounds 247.3m).
But he warned: 'A full recovery is not yet in prospect. Profits so far this
year are only marginally ahead of last year's levels.'
Group profits were also depressed by a sharp decline in interest receivable
from Pounds 4.45m to Pounds 384,000.
This was due mainly to the group's decision to withdraw cash from short-term
deposits and increase borrowing from Pounds 122m to Pounds 132m.
Earnings per share showed an adjusted increase of 9.9 per cent from 13.93p
to 15.31p.
A recommended final dividend of 6.25p (6.1p) gives a total for the year of
9.5p, against 9.35p.
Capital expenditure fell by 58 per cent to Pounds 31.5m (Pounds 75.3m) as
the group consolidated its existing property portfolio rather than continue
with rapid expansion of the hotels business.
Vaux and Ward Breweries, accounting for 44 per cent of group turnover,
achieved a 10.2 increase in profits from Pounds 19.5m to Pounds 21.5m.
Vaux Inns - comprising the group's 127 managed houses - saw profits rise 3.4
per cent to Pounds 4.9m (Pounds 4.7m) on turnover of Pounds 37.4m (Pounds
36.6m).
For the first time since embarking on an expansion drive in 1987, Swallow
Hotels reported better than expected results.
Profits rose 10.5 per cent to Pounds 13.8m (Pounds 12.5m) on sales of Pounds
79.8m (Pounds 77.9m).
In spite of the improvement, Sir Paul said recent bookings had been
disappointing.
St Andrews Homes, the nursing home operator and smallest part of the group,
saw profits increase from Pounds 4.1m to Pounds 4.6m on turnover of Pounds
14m (Pounds 13m).
COMMENT
Inclement conditions in Vaux's trading area have not dented the group's
conviction that it is well placed to profit from a recovery. That confidence
was reflected yesterday by a dividend increase ahead of market expectations.
A lower than forecast tax charge of Pounds 5.5m (Pounds 5.99m) also
surprised analysts. But in the absence of an imminent recovery, profits next
year are not expected to exceed Pounds 30m on a forward multiple of 15.6,
making the shares seem expensive.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Vaux Group.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2082 Malt Beverages.
    P7011 Hotels and Motels.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>FIN  Annual report.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 20
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT934-2157</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DLOCPAESFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931215
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / UK Company News: Pounds 51m raised for Fairbairn European
Trust
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Providence Capitol has raised Pounds 51m for the Fairbairn European Smaller
Companies Index Trust, the first in a planned series of indexed investment
trusts, writes Philip Coggan.
The trust will track the James Capel European Smaller Companies Index Trust,
which covers 17 countries and 1,000 stocks.
Dealings in the shares are expected to start on December 16.
</TEXT>
